name: MariaDB Server
description: MariaDB server is a community developed fork of MySQL server. Started by core members of the original MySQL teamy .MariaDB is a relational database it provides an SQL interface for accessing data.
sites_https_justification:
website: https://mariadb.com/kb/en/documentation/
repository: github
download: https://mariadb.org/download/
contribution_justification: https://github.com/MariaDB/server/blob/10.6/CONTRIBUTING.md
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/MariaDB/server/blob/10.6/COPYING>.
floss_license_justification: The GPL-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The GPL-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://mariadb.com/kb/en/documentation/
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: The source code on github is the working version containing unreleased code.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_tags_justification:
git tags are used - https://github.com/MariaDB/server/tags

https://mariadb.org/about/#maintenance-policy -> Semantic versioning -> "in spirit" in the server. Compatibility is a core essential component. Patch releases do contain new features in backwards compatible manner (extended syntax or new options that have their previous behaviour as default).
release_notes_vulns_justification: There is an overall list https://mariadb.com/kb/en/security/  and release notes will list CVE references like https://mariadb.com/kb/en/mariadb-1056-release-notes/
report_responses_justification:
createdDate  > startOfMonth(-12M) and project=MDEV and type=Bug 
https://jira.mariadb.org/issues/?jql=createdDate%20 > startOfMonth(-12M) and project%3DMDEV and type%3DBug
is 2628 entries

and (status not in (Rejected,"In Progress","In Review",Confirmed,Closed) and labels not in (need_feedback))
is 313 (of which many include discussion, its just hard to query that critieria)
enhancement_responses_justification:
createdDate  > startOfMonth(-12M) and project=MDEV and type=Task
https://jira.mariadb.org/issues/?jql=createdDate%20%20%3E%20startOfMonth(-12M)%20and%20project%3DMDEV%20and%20type%3DTask
463

+ and (status not in (Rejected,"In Progress","In Review",Confirmed,Closed) and labels not in (need_feedback))
= 75
report_archive_justification: https://jira.mariadb.org is publicly searchable and has been there from very early in the development of MariaDB
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: https://mariadb.org/about/#security-policy list private email or HackerOne Program.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat:
MariaDB release schedule follows the MySQL schedule so we can pick up their vulnerabilities. e.g. 10.5.7 (https://mariadb.com/kb/en/mariadb-1057-release-notes/) released on 3 November 2020 includes CVE-2020-14812 (oracle https://www.oracle.com/security-alerts/cpuoct2020.html#AppendixMSQL released this notice in October 2020) (https://security.netapp.com/advisory/ntap-20201023-0003/ lists 23 October 2020 as initial release).

https://mariadb.com/kb/en/mariadb-1056-changelog/ shows a few days from the fix to release.

recent presentation: https://mariadb.org/minifest2020/security/
build_floss_tools_justification:
Open source build tools are https://mariadb.com/kb/en/Build_Environment_Setup_for_Linux/

Similar tools exist for non-Linux, including windows (https://mariadb.com/kb/en/Building_MariaDB_on_Windows/)
test_justification:
Test suites are in the code - https://github.com/MariaDB/server/tree/10.5/mysql-test
Documentation on running tests https://github.com/MariaDB/server/blob/10.5/mysql-test/README and https://github.com/MariaDB/server/blob/10.5/mysql-test/README
test_invocation_justification:
"ctest ." will run a set of unit tests but not the whole mysql-test test of tests.
There probably isn't a hugely standard way for client/server C/C++ tests.
test_most_justification: Writing tests is part of the development process. While there isn't full coverage tests cover significant parts of the functionality.
tests_documented_added_justification: Tests are part of PR and commits per https://mariadb.com/kb/en/contributing-code/
warnings_justification:
ASAN/MASN options are there that result in cflags https://github.com/MariaDB/server/blob/10.5/CMakeLists.txt#L199-L262

While they default to off, the [test_policy] and the CI will check these.

Significant use of C/C++ attributes to enable complier detection of false values occurs - https://github.com/MariaDB/server/blob/10.6/storage/innobase/include/dict0dict.h#L113
warnings_strict_justification: https://github.com/MariaDB/server/blob/10.5/cmake/maintainer.cmake warnings enabled and are generally noticed and addressed
test_continuous_integration_justificatio:
All committed code triggers builds. On main branches and on developer test branches (bb-10.X-description).
https://buildbot.mariadb.org/#/grid?branch=10.5

buildbot.askmonty.org/buildbot/grid?category=main&branch=10.5
discussion_justification:
GitHub pull requests.
Bugs/Features/Issues is https://jira.mariadb.org/projects/MDEV/issues being a free to register web site.
english_justification:
English documentation https://mariadb.com/kb/en/documentation/
Bug reports and code comments are almost always done in English https://jira.mariadb.org/projects/MDEV/issues
hardened_site_justification: // One or more of the required security hardening headers is missing.
implementation_languages: C++, C, Perl, Yacc, CMake, Shell

name: ORAN SC: Near-RT RIC
description: The near-RT RIC (RT = realtime  RIC = RAN intelligent controller  RAN = Radio Access Network  O-RAN = Open RAN  SC = software community) Platform is a software based near‐real‐time micro‐service‐based platform for hosting micro-service-based applications - the xApps - that run on the near-RT RIC platform. xApps are not part of the RIC platform and developed in projects that are separate from the near-RT RIC platform project. The near-RT RIC platform is providing xApps the infrastructure for controlling a distributed collection of RAN base stations (eNB, gNB, CU, DU) in a region via the O-RAN alliance's E2 protocol ("southbound").

name: SBK
description: Storage Benchmark Kit
description_good_justification: The SBK (Storage Benchmark Kit) is an open source software frame-work for the performance benchmarking of any storage system. If you are curious to measure the maximum throughput performance of your storage device/system, then SBK is the right software for you. The SBK itself a very high-performance benchmark tool/framework. It massively writes the data to storage system and reads the data from storage system. The SBK supports multi writers and readers and also the End to End latency benchmarking. The percentiles are calculated for complete data written/read without any sampling; hence the percentiles are 100% accurate.
